# Getting Started with Pandas

To start working with pandas, the first thing I did was import the library:

import pandas as pd

# 📊 Understanding Data Structures in Pandas

While learning pandas, I understood that there are two main data structures:

DataFrame
Series
🔹 DataFrame

A DataFrame is like a table that stores data in rows and columns. Each value in the table belongs to a specific row and column.

For example:

pd.DataFrame({'Yes': [50, 21], 'No': [131, 2]})

In this example:

The value 131 is in row 0 under the "No" column
The value 50 is in row 0 under the "Yes" column

DataFrames can store different types of data, not just numbers. They can also store strings:

pd.DataFrame({
    'Bob': ['I liked it.', 'It was awful.'],
    'Sue': ['Pretty good.', 'Bland.']
})
🔹 Creating DataFrames

I learned that the most common way to create a DataFrame is using a dictionary, where:

Keys = column names
Values = list of data

By default, pandas assigns row numbers starting from 0.

But we can also define our own row labels using the index:

pd.DataFrame({
    'Bob': ['I liked it.', 'It was awful.'],
    'Sue': ['Pretty good.', 'Bland.']
}, index=['Product A', 'Product B'])

Here, instead of numeric rows, we use custom labels like Product A and Product B.

🔹 Series

A Series is basically a single column of data. It is like a list but with an index.

Example:

pd.Series([1, 2, 3, 4, 5])

We can also assign custom labels and give it a name:

pd.Series(
    [30, 35, 40],
    index=['2015 Sales', '2016 Sales', '2017 Sales'],
    name='Product A'
)

So, I understood that:
👉 A DataFrame is just multiple Series combined together

📂 Reading Data from Files

In real-world scenarios, we usually don’t create data manually. Instead, we work with existing datasets.

One of the most common file formats is CSV (Comma-Separated Values).

🔹 Reading a CSV File

To load a CSV file into pandas, I used:

wine_reviews = pd.read_csv("file_path.csv")
🔹 Checking Data Size

To understand the dataset size, I used:

wine_reviews.shape

This returns:

Number of rows
Number of columns
🔹 Viewing Data

To quickly look at the first few rows of the dataset:

wine_reviews.head()

This helps in understanding the structure and columns of the data.

🔹 Setting Index Column

Sometimes the dataset already has a column that should act as an index. In that case, I used:

wine_reviews = pd.read_csv("file_path.csv", index_col=0)

This tells pandas to use the first column as the index instead of creating a new one.

✅ Summary
Imported pandas using import pandas as pd
Learned about DataFrame (table) and Series (single column)
Created data using dictionaries and lists
Used index to customize row labels
Loaded real-world data using read_csv()
Explored data using .shape and .head()
